    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-01-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-01-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="439"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d439">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 741.8215/31.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">British Ambassador</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">British Embassy</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-01-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 24, 1911</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I beg to acknowledge the
                    receipt of your personal note of yesterday, in reply to mine of the 16th,
                    informing me of the instructions sent on the 19th instant to the American
                    minister at Monrovia regarding the question of the Kanré-Lahun boundary.</p>
                <p>I have much pleasure in expressing to you my thanks for your courteous action in
                    the matter and the friendly spirit in which you have met the request of His
                    Majesty’s Government.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">James Bryce.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
